ncerns. These original essays range from how to conduct research on youth in ways that can be empowering for them, to issues of writing and representation, to respecting boundaries and to dealing with issues of risk and responsibility to those interviewed. For anyone doing research or working with children and young adults, Representing Youth offers an indispensable guide to many of the unique dilemmas that research with kids entails.Contributors include: Amy L. Best, Sari Knopp Biklen, Elizabeth Chin, Susan Driver, Marc Flacks, Kathryn Gold Hadley, Madeline Leonard, C.J. Pascoe, Rebecca Raby, Alyssa Richman, Jessica Taft, Michael Ungar, Yvonne Vissing, and Stephani Etheridge Woodson.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aChildrenxResearch. 0aChildrenxStudy and teaching. 0aYouthxResearch. 0aYouthxStudy and teaching. 4aThese. 4aboundaries. 4aconduct. 4adealing. 4aempowering. 4aessays. 4afrom. 4ainterviewed. 4aissues. 4aoriginal. 4arange. 4arepresentation. 4aresearch. 4arespecting. 4aresponsibility. 4arisk. 4athat. 4athem. 4athose. 4aways. 4awith. 4awriting. 4ayouth. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Research.2bisacsh1 aBest, Amy L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814739204423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814739204.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK